Custom Memory Allocator
A from-scratch implementation of malloc, free, realloc, and calloc in C. No standard library allocator functions are used. Everything runs on top of raw sbrk and mmap system calls.
Built as part of a summer portfolio project to understand what actually happens when you call malloc.

What this is
When you write malloc(32) in C, the standard library does a lot of work behind the scenes: it finds a free chunk of heap memory, tracks it, and hands you a pointer. This project implements all of that from scratch.
The allocator supports three different strategies for finding free memory, and they all get benchmarked against each other to show the trade-offs between speed and fragmentation.

Features
	•	Three allocation strategies: first-fit, best-fit, and buddy system
	•	Block splitting to avoid wasting memory in large free blocks
	•	Block coalescing to merge adjacent free blocks after freeing
	•	Alignment to 8-byte boundaries on all returned pointers
	•	Double-free detection using magic number headers
	•	Invalid pointer detection on free
	•	In-place realloc growth when the next block is free
	•	Thread safety via a POSIX mutex
	•	Benchmarking harness comparing throughput and fragmentation across all three strategies

