How to build
# build and run tests
gcc -Wall -Wextra -pthread -o test allocator.c buddy.c test.c && ./test

# build and run benchmarks
gcc -Wall -Wextra -pthread -O2 -o benchmark allocator.c buddy.c benchmark.c && ./benchmark
The -O2 flag on the benchmark build matters. You want compiler optimisations on when measuring performance, not a debug build.

How it works
The block header
Every chunk of managed memory has a small header placed right before it:
typedef struct Block {
    size_t   size;      // usable bytes after this header
    int      is_free;   // 1 = available, 0 = in use
    uint32_t magic;     // corruption and double-free detection
    struct Block *next;
    struct Block *prev;
} Block;
On 64-bit systems this is 32 bytes. The layout in memory looks like:
[ header ][ user data ][ header ][ user data ]...
Given a user pointer, recovering the header is always (Block*)ptr - 1. This one pattern is used everywhere.
The three strategies
First-fit scans the block list and returns the first free block that is big enough. Fast, but tends to fragment the beginning of the heap with small leftovers over time.
Best-fit scans the entire list and returns the smallest block that fits. Produces less fragmentation than first-fit but is slower because it always does a full scan.
Buddy system is a completely different approach. Every block is a power-of-two size. When memory is needed, a large block is repeatedly halved until the smallest power-of-two that fits is reached. When freed, a block merges with its "buddy" (the other half of the split) if the buddy is also free. Finding the buddy uses XOR arithmetic and is O(1). Allocation is O(log n). The trade-off is internal fragmentation: a 33-byte request gets a 64-byte block, wasting 31 bytes.
Switching strategies
set_strategy(STRATEGY_FIRST_FIT);   // default
set_strategy(STRATEGY_BEST_FIT);
set_strategy(STRATEGY_BUDDY);
Safety features
Two magic number constants are used to detect memory bugs:
#define MAGIC_ALLOC 0xDEADBEEF   // block is in use
#define MAGIC_FREE  0xDEADDEAD   // block was freed
Every block gets MAGIC_ALLOC stamped on it when allocated. On free, the magic field is checked first. If it is already MAGIC_FREE, the call is a double-free and is rejected with an error message. If it is anything other than MAGIC_ALLOC, the pointer is invalid and is also rejected. Neither case crashes the program.

