What I learned
A few things that were not obvious going in:
Coalescing cannot call malloc or free internally. The first version of coalesce called my_free to mark a block as free before merging it. That causes infinite recursion because my_free calls coalesce, which calls my_free, and so on. Coalescing has to do pointer surgery directly on the existing blocks.
The magic field has to be reset on reuse. When my_malloc reuses a freed block, it has to stamp MAGIC_ALLOC back on it. Missing this meant the next free call would see MAGIC_FREE and incorrectly report a double-free, which is exactly what showed up in the thread safety test before the fix.
Unlocking before calling another locked function. my_realloc sometimes needs to call my_malloc and my_free internally for its fallback path. Since all three functions lock the same mutex, my_realloc has to unlock before making those calls. Forgetting this causes a deadlock that only shows up under concurrent load.
Best-fit does not always produce less fragmentation. The theory says best-fit should fragment less than first-fit. In practice, because best-fit always picks the tightest match, it tends to leave many tiny unusable remainders. On random-size workloads the difference is real (0.19 vs 0.34) but best-fit is not the clear winner the theory suggests.

Known limitations
	•	Single global mutex: all allocations are serialised. Under high thread contention this is the main bottleneck. Per-thread arenas (how jemalloc and tcmalloc work) would fix this.
	•	No mmap fallback for large allocations: everything goes through sbrk. Real allocators use mmap for requests above ~128KB so those chunks can be returned to the OS on free.
	•	O(n) allocation for first-fit and best-fit: both scan the full free list. Segregated free lists (one list per size class) would make typical allocations O(1).
	•	Fixed-size buddy pool: the buddy system is backed by a static 64KB array. A real implementation would grow on demand.

